Copilot AI Nov 30, 2025

There was a problem hiding this comment.

Choose a reason for hiding this comment

The reason will be displayed to describe this comment to others. Learn more.

This name parsing logic has an edge case issue. When name.trim().split("\\s+") is called on a string with only whitespace, it will return an array with one empty string element, not an empty array. This means names.isEmpty() will be false, and names.get(0) will return an empty string, resulting in a firstName of "". Consider adding a check: if (StringUtils.hasText(name)) { followed by checking !names.isEmpty() && StringUtils.hasText(names.get(0)) before setting firstName.

Copilot AI Nov 30, 2025

There was a problem hiding this comment.

Choose a reason for hiding this comment

The reason will be displayed to describe this comment to others. Learn more.

The error message formatting has a potential issue when the file size is not an exact multiple of 1MB. For example, if maxSizeBytes is 5242880 (5MB), the calculation 5242880 / (1024 * 1024) will result in 5, but if maxSizeBytes were set to 5000000, it would display 4 MB limit instead of the actual ~4.77 MB. Consider using a decimal format or reporting the limit in bytes for accuracy, e.g., String.format("Profile picture exceeds the limit of %d bytes", maxSizeBytes).

Suggested change
.message(String.format("Profile picture exceeds %d MB limit", maxSizeBytes / (1024 * 1024)))
.message(String.format("Profile picture exceeds %.1f MB limit", maxSizeBytes / (1024.0 * 1024.0)))

[nitpick] The path traversal validation looks good, but there's a potential issue with the order of operations. If Paths.get(filePath) throws an InvalidPathException, the SecurityException will be thrown, which is good. However, the validation for empty strings should ideally happen before attempting to create a Path object. While this works correctly, it's more defensive to check for empty/null before attempting to parse. The current order is acceptable but consider moving line 24-26 before line 27 for better defensive programming.

Copilot AI Nov 30, 2025

Choose a reason for hiding this comment

The reason will be displayed to describe this comment to others. Learn more.

[nitpick] The allowed extensions set includes "bmp" which is typically a large, uncompressed image format. Including BMP in a profile picture upload system could lead to storage issues and slower page loads. Consider whether BMP support is actually needed, or if it should be excluded to encourage users to upload more web-optimized formats. If BMP is intentionally supported, consider adding size validation that's stricter for BMP files.

Suggested change
private static final java.util.Set<String> ALLOWED_IMAGE_EXTENSIONS = java.util.Set.of("png", "jpg", "jpeg", "gif", "webp", "bmp");
